 First, we need to find out how many questions she got right on the first test. Since she got 60% of the questions correct, we can calculate this as follows
 \text{Number of questions she got right} = 60\% \times 70 \text{ questions} 
 \text{Number of questions she got right} = 0.6 \times 70 \text{ questions} 
 \text{Number of questions she got right} = 42 \text{ questions} 

Next, we need to find out how many questions she needs to get right on the second test to move on to the 7th grade. Since she needs to get 70% of the total questions right, we can calculate this as follows
 \text{Number of questions she needs to get right} = 70\% \times 40 \text{ questions} 
 \text{Number of questions she needs to get right} = 0.7 \times 40 \text{ questions} 
 \text{Number of questions she needs to get right} = 28 \text{ questions} 

Therefore, Audrey needs to get 28 questions right on the second test to move on to the 7th grade.
